---
title: "Practice Quizz - Probability"
---




Some questions below will require you to do calculations. Enter only the numeric result in the answer field.




::: {.cell}

:::

::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which are good practice habits when using probability in ecology? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-375bf5e84a856fdda7cfebcb0130d8c8' data-answer='aAcZU0oESQlp'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='375bf5e84a856fdda7cfebcb0130d8c8'></input><span>Assume everything is independent to simplify</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='375bf5e84a856fdda7cfebcb0130d8c8'></input><span>Define events clearly before calculating probabilities</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='375bf5e84a856fdda7cfebcb0130d8c8'></input><span>Avoid assuming independence without justification</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='375bf5e84a856fdda7cfebcb0130d8c8'></input><span>Use complements/unions to avoid double-counting</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Good practice is conceptual: define events, choose the correct rule, and justify assumptions. Unjustified independence can badly mislead inference.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


During a salmon count, 12 of 48 fish are Chinook salmon. Estimate P(Chinook) using relative frequency.

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-53ed0beff7b394ffb7623bcf1e8a6501' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='bhFVSgJXRzs='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Relative frequency estimate is count / total = 12 / 48 = 0.25. This is an empirical estimate that would stabilize with larger samples.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Given P(A | B) = 0.30 and P(B) = 0.20, compute P(A ∩ B).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-53e7fa2b609c152abd3bda6a0805c9cf' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='bhFVGVZXED8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Multiplication rule: P(A ∩ B) = P(A|B)P(B) = 0.30 × 0.20 = 0.06.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A ∪ B) = 1, compute P((A ∪ B)ᶜ).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-08ab171f482e546e52d598710d7938a6' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='axpRQGw='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

If union covers the whole sample space (i.e., P(A ∪ B) = 1), its complement is impossible, so P((A ∪ B)ᶜ) = 0.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


What do we call the set of all possible outcomes?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-9687e0fdf27cec867ef94b1181f83f8b' size='31' data-answer='YhRmazlDTD81QWoCCBNUU2s5FRNvMUJsSFAFXW86S0gdFGU='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The **sample space** contains all possible outcomes for the process you are modeling (e.g., {detected, not detected} for one sample).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If A and B are mutually exclusive and both have positive probability, which are true? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-161a26fe5b2e61309f801e67ed0f1ac3' data-answer='agcdUB4GSlRo'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='161a26fe5b2e61309f801e67ed0f1ac3'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) = 0</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='161a26fe5b2e61309f801e67ed0f1ac3'></input><span>A and B cannot be independent</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='161a26fe5b2e61309f801e67ed0f1ac3'></input><span>P(A | B) = P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='161a26fe5b2e61309f801e67ed0f1ac3'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B)</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Disjoint events have zero overlap and additive union. With positive probabilities, independence would require P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B) > 0, which contradicts the fact that disjoint events have no overlap; so they cannot be independent. P(A | B) must be 0 if B occurs because A and B are disjoint.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A) = 1, compute P(Aᶜ).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-3cdb26fcb4be06f758e3bb04705a7df7' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='aEFUQG8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

A is a certain event, so complement impossible: P(Aᶜ) = 1 − P(A) = 1 - 1 = 0.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In an ecological sampling scenario, P(A) = P(detect sample 1) = 0.4 and P(B) = P(detect sample 2) = 0.4. Assuming independence, compute P(detect in both samples).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-cf1198d3382d177b5bb649be85819143' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='OEQBHwgORm4='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Under independence: P(A ∩ B) = 0.4 × 0.4 = 0.16. In practice, subsequent sampling events may be dependent, but the arithmetic illustrates the product rule.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


What is the term for 'not A'?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-8e79b3f52ab90b913763d2bd699a16a3' size='23' data-answer='Y0dpZT5ATG5xAj9WXRJVVF5SWEc4bhFOEhtk'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The **complement** of A (or Aᶜ), is the event that A does not occur.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Two events are independent if:


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-4c6aed38d9939693e12fd0f153849e82' data-answer='b1MaUElUHwg5'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='4c6aed38d9939693e12fd0f153849e82'></input><span>They cannot occur together</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='4c6aed38d9939693e12fd0f153849e82'></input><span>Knowing one occurred gives no information about the other</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='4c6aed38d9939693e12fd0f153849e82'></input><span>Their probabilities sum to 1</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='4c6aed38d9939693e12fd0f153849e82'></input><span>They have equal probability</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Independence is about **no change in probability** when you learn information: P(A | B) = P(A). Independent events can co‑occur; it is mutually exclusive events that cannot. Equal probabilities or summing to 1 are not definitions of independence.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statements about “AND” vs “OR” are correct? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-b67840097e286111ec23c66994cc7bbf' data-answer='OQcbCBgBHAlq'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='b67840097e286111ec23c66994cc7bbf'></input><span>A ∩ B means A AND B</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='b67840097e286111ec23c66994cc7bbf'></input><span>A ∪ B excludes cases where both occur</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='b67840097e286111ec23c66994cc7bbf'></input><span>A ∪ B means A OR B (inclusive)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='b67840097e286111ec23c66994cc7bbf'></input><span>A ∩ B is always larger than A</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Intersection is AND. Union is inclusive OR (A, B, or both). Union does not exclude overlap. Intersection is a subset of A, so it cannot be larger than A.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


What word indicates conditioning in a probability statement?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-4564dea7b11f06abdbd0fdc4b92ef064' size='20' data-answer='bxdoaDgWS2wlVmwPRlMPPjgRThREOQ=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The word **given** signals conditional probability, like P(A | B) = probability of A given B.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a bird point-count, P(detect) = 0.65. Compute P(not detect).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-ae91000422f90265ff619531bcd7c38b' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='OkcJHwMFEmk='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Use complement rule: 1 − 0.65 = 0.35.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a bird point-count, wind reduces detectability. Let A = “species detected”, B = “windy”. Which statements are plausible? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-6dae790ce8abf6b0d9a3bbe4a8db281d' data-answer='bVVNVRsIHFM4'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='6dae790ce8abf6b0d9a3bbe4a8db281d'></input><span>A and B may be dependent</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='6dae790ce8abf6b0d9a3bbe4a8db281d'></input><span>This automatically proves the species is absent when windy</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='6dae790ce8abf6b0d9a3bbe4a8db281d'></input><span>P(A | B) < P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='6dae790ce8abf6b0d9a3bbe4a8db281d'></input><span>P(A | B) must equal P(A)</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Wind can make birds harder to hear/see, reducing detection probability. That means P(detect | windy) can be lower than overall P(detect), indicating dependence. But lower detection does not prove absence. Instead, it reflects the observation process.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


A stream dries during summer (event A) and juvenile salmon experience mortality (event B). Which statements are reasonable? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-bdbb23ad90d13a71ec631cef9cecbf39' data-answer='OVVOUx4CTVRk'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='bdbb23ad90d13a71ec631cef9cecbf39'></input><span>If A occurs, B may become more likely</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='bdbb23ad90d13a71ec631cef9cecbf39'></input><span>Knowing B occurred could provide information about whether A occurred</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='bdbb23ad90d13a71ec631cef9cecbf39'></input><span>A and B are likely dependent</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='bdbb23ad90d13a71ec631cef9cecbf39'></input><span>A and B are certainly independent</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Drying reduces habitat and can increase stress, crowding, and predation risk, so mortality may become more likely. That is **dependence**: learning A changes beliefs about B and vice‑versa. Independence is not automatic and it must be justified.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


You know P(A) = 0.3, P(B) = 0.7, and P(A ∩ B) = 0.4. Which statement is correct?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-b6a961297f789ff91d1f080105657497' data-answer='OQZNCBoBHglq'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b6a961297f789ff91d1f080105657497'></input><span>P(A | B) = 0.4</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b6a961297f789ff91d1f080105657497'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) = 0.6</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b6a961297f789ff91d1f080105657497'></input><span>A and B are mutually exclusive</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b6a961297f789ff91d1f080105657497'></input><span>A and B are independent because 0.3 × 0.7 = 0.21</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Compute the union using the addition rule: P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A ∩ B) = 0.3 + 0.7 − 0.4 = 0.6. They are not mutually exclusive (intersection is not 0). They are not independent (0.3 × 0.7 = 0.21, not 0.4). Also P(A | B) = 0.4 / 0.7 = 0.57, not 0.4.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A | B) ≠ P(A), what is the relationship between A and B?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-f197888ecf08804273b73b4cc273535e' size='22' data-answer='PRNna2RLEj4nAm1dSFVaVlJdFmtvER5HQW8='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

If conditioning on B changes the probability of A, then A and B are **dependent** (associated).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


A researcher says: “Because two events happen on different days, they must be independent.” What is the best response?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-b2ed319799587f158a098f3bf7a217ef' data-answer='OQJJVB8BFQZk'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b2ed319799587f158a098f3bf7a217ef'></input><span>Correct — independence only depends on sample size</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b2ed319799587f158a098f3bf7a217ef'></input><span>It depends only on whether events are rare</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b2ed319799587f158a098f3bf7a217ef'></input><span>Correct — different days guarantees independence</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b2ed319799587f158a098f3bf7a217ef'></input><span>Incorrect — independence is an assumption; shared drivers (e.g., environmentalc conditons) can create dependence</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Different days do **not** guarantee independence. If both days share conditions (weather, flow, observer, habitat), then learning about one day can change probabilities about the other. Independence must be justified by mechanism or design, not by calendar time. Independence has nothing to do with sample size or an event being rare.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a landscape study 50% of sites are forested (event F, so P(F) = 0.5) and 75% of sites have a stream  (event S, so P(S) = 0.75). Among forested sites, 60% have a stream, so P(S | F) = 0.6. What is the probability that a site is forested given that it has a stream?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-8446d02b4573577451c42fcdfed67b47' data-answer='YwQYBkgBHlJp'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8446d02b4573577451c42fcdfed67b47'></input><span>0.1</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8446d02b4573577451c42fcdfed67b47'></input><span>0.7</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8446d02b4573577451c42fcdfed67b47'></input><span>0.4</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8446d02b4573577451c42fcdfed67b47'></input><span>0.5</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

You are asked to find P(F | S). So, applying Bayes’ rule:

P(F | S) = [P(S | F) × P(F)] / P(S)
          = (0.6 × 0.5) / 0.75
          = 0.4

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


What is the name of the rule P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A∩B)?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-2e2d8288cee61a55f7e0fedf40c8187a' size='40' data-answer='aUdsOGRBEmMiBDhSVQhBXAlZOWwVTz80Rm0WVFRkaxIYGW44SxhjeQI4AVJYFVxaCGs5Q0xBRjs='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

**Addition** rule.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A) = 0.7, what is the minimum possible value of P(A ∪ B)? HINT: it helps to draw Venn diagrams to come up with solution.

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-30ad6278ab3f1e5d6c59a467fea7f84b' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='aBJRSgEQag=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Union contains A, so it cannot be smaller than P(A). Minimum occurs when B is a subset of A.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A | B) > P(A), what does that suggest?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-595e956e659946b7e1ec6873ae4f3196' data-answer='bgkZVRUEGlVr'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='595e956e659946b7e1ec6873ae4f3196'></input><span>B makes A less likely</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='595e956e659946b7e1ec6873ae4f3196'></input><span>A and B must be independent</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='595e956e659946b7e1ec6873ae4f3196'></input><span>B provides information that increases the probability of A</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='595e956e659946b7e1ec6873ae4f3196'></input><span>A and B must be mutually exclusive</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Knowing B increases the probability that A happens. It does not imply mutual exclusivity, and it contradicts independence.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A) = 0.2 and P(B) = 0.3 and A and B are mutually exclusive, compute P(A ∪ B).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-9d8545742ddd6f67cd0ee39264d63c58' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='YkYIGwEXag=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

For disjoint events, union is additive: 0.2 + 0.3 = 0.5.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


What is the term for events where knowing one occurred does not change the probability of the other?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-7b78b4a3de25c31fac44fe0a40573e9e' size='24' data-answer='bEBpZD5HS2gtDG9bB1ZBAw8HUVoSOWwSHhQXag=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

*Independent* events means P(A | B) = P(A), equivalently P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statement is an axiom (always true) in probability theory?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-000101ae0dc145d52e06f4e45f59039a' data-answer='awAcABwBTVVt'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='000101ae0dc145d52e06f4e45f59039a'></input><span>Probabilities must sum to 0 across events</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='000101ae0dc145d52e06f4e45f59039a'></input><span>The probability of the sample space is 1</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='000101ae0dc145d52e06f4e45f59039a'></input><span>Probabilities can be negative for rare events</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='000101ae0dc145d52e06f4e45f59039a'></input><span>Probabilities depend on measurement units</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

One axiom is **normalization**: if S is the sample space (all possible outcomes), then P(S)=1. Other axioms include non‑negativity (P(A) ≥ 0) and additivity for disjoint events. Units matter for measurements (e.g., °C vs °F), but not for probability axioms.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In words, what does the symbol ∪ mean?

<input class='webex-solveme regex' id='webex-e600395dc66a15781368eacc6e04b32f' size='32' data-answer='PhRubG9KHz82Q2sPWFpZZG1AHEQ5PRBJbSpfaRBvbhVPEhJt'/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

A ∪ B is the **union**, that is outcomes where either A **or** B occurs.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Given P(A) = 0.6, P(B) = 0.5, P(A ∩ B) = 0.4, compute P(A ∪ B).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-5c16ae2fa65f317ac9fb93a5aa354009' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='bkEBGFZHbw=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Use addition rule for overlapping events: P(A ∪ B) = 0.6 + 0.5 − 0.4 = 0.7 (subtract overlap once to avoid double-counting).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If P(A) = 0.4, compute P(Aᶜ).

<input class='webex-solveme nospaces' id='webex-6bebc4effc7bebc8d6eda04fa7d448b2' data-tol='0' size='20' data-answer='bUBVTFUWOA=='/>

:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Complement rule: 1 − 0.4 = 0.6.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a fish survey, event A = “a randomly selected captured fish is female.” If P(A) = 0.40, what is P(Aᶜ)?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-8538d0e7169adae79b7bd55be631f6a9' data-answer='YwUfCEgASQZs'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8538d0e7169adae79b7bd55be631f6a9'></input><span>0.40</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8538d0e7169adae79b7bd55be631f6a9'></input><span>0.00</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8538d0e7169adae79b7bd55be631f6a9'></input><span>1.40</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='8538d0e7169adae79b7bd55be631f6a9'></input><span>0.60</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Use the complement rule: P(Aᶜ) = 1 − P(A) = 1 − 0.40 = 0.60.  
Interpretation: in the long run, about 60% of captured fish would be non‑female under the same sampling process (not necessarily in every sample).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statement is always true for any events A and B?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-21ef3ccccae550f6e0384d4f2a70b807' data-answer='aQFJVx9TT1M+'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21ef3ccccae550f6e0384d4f2a70b807'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) ≥ P(A)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21ef3ccccae550f6e0384d4f2a70b807'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) ≤ P(A)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21ef3ccccae550f6e0384d4f2a70b807'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) always</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21ef3ccccae550f6e0384d4f2a70b807'></input><span>P(A | B) > 1</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The intersection (A∩B) is a subset of A, so it cannot be more probable than A: P(A ∩ B) ≤ P(A). The union equals the sum only when events are disjoint. Probabilities cannot exceed 1.

:::

