:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Computation: P(A | B) = P(A ∩ B) / P(B) = 0.12 / 0.30 = 0.4.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a nest monitoring project, event A = “the nest is predated this season.” If P(A) = 0.30, what does the complement event Aᶜ represent?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-dc2219c77c2d5e48b8e19519023574db' data-answer='P1MeAx0JTwdq'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dc2219c77c2d5e48b8e19519023574db'></input><span>The nest is present</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dc2219c77c2d5e48b8e19519023574db'></input><span>The nest is *not* predated this season</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dc2219c77c2d5e48b8e19519023574db'></input><span>The nest is successful</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dc2219c77c2d5e48b8e19519023574db'></input><span>The predator is absent from the region</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Aᶜ is “not A.” So Aᶜ means **no predation** in that season.  
NOTE: “not predated” is not automatically the same as “successful” unless you define success as “not predated” (you might also have abandonment, wildfires, etc.). Clear event definitions matter.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Suppose P(A ∩ B) = P(A). What does this imply about the relationship between A and B?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-2b43f252085afd3facec64940e122f14' data-answer='aVMYA0oCGQJt'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2b43f252085afd3facec64940e122f14'></input><span>Whenever A happens, B also happens (A ⊆ B)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2b43f252085afd3facec64940e122f14'></input><span>A and B are independent</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2b43f252085afd3facec64940e122f14'></input><span>Whenever B happens, A also happens (B ⊆ A)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2b43f252085afd3facec64940e122f14'></input><span>A and B cannot co-occur</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

If the intersection equals P(A), then **all of A is inside B** (i.e., A ⊆ B).  
That is, whenever A happens, B must also happen. This is a useful logical interpretation that can appear in ecological event definitions. For example, if A is "juvenile of sockeye" and B is "sockeye", then A is a subset of B. If you sample a fish and it is a sockeye juvenile, then it is also certainly (i.e., P(B) = 1) a sockeye. It follows that P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B) = P(A).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


A snorkel survey defines A = “juvenile salmon observed” and B = “water temperature > 20°C at survey time.” Which interpretation is correct?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-33e71f1c0556787982ff76bdaaaf4cc0' data-answer='aANJBx1WHVJt'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='33e71f1c0556787982ff76bdaaaf4cc0'></input><span>P(B | A) is the probability juveniles are observed given T > 20°C</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='33e71f1c0556787982ff76bdaaaf4cc0'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) is the probability juveniles are observed or T > 20°C</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='33e71f1c0556787982ff76bdaaaf4cc0'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) is the probability juveniles are observed and T > 20°C</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='33e71f1c0556787982ff76bdaaaf4cc0'></input><span>P(A | B) is the probability juveniles are observed given T > 20°C</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

P(A | B) reads “A given B.” Here: probability of observing juveniles **given** temperature exceeds 20°C. Be careful with symbols: ∩ means AND, ∪ means OR (inclusive). This is a common source of mistakes.

:::

