::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which are always true for any events A and B? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-8e13f44142f50446c04d32e407cd7e48' data-answer='Y1QdAkoFGAFp'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='8e13f44142f50446c04d32e407cd7e48'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) ≥ P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='8e13f44142f50446c04d32e407cd7e48'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) ≤ P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='8e13f44142f50446c04d32e407cd7e48'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) ≤ P(B)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='8e13f44142f50446c04d32e407cd7e48'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) always</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Intersection is a subset of each event, so it cannot be larger than either P(A) or P(B). Union contains A, so it cannot be smaller than A. Union equals sum only when A and B are disjoint / mutually exclusive (i.e., no overlap).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


An ecologist says: 

“Before I collect new data, I can still assign a probability that a stream reach is occupied by bull trout based on prior surveys and expert knowledge.” 

This statement aligns most closely with which definition of probability?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-9d7618e256099eb232b4f8515cdc104e' data-answer='YlQbBh0ISQNo'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='9d7618e256099eb232b4f8515cdc104e'></input><span>Bayesian: probability cannot be updated with data</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='9d7618e256099eb232b4f8515cdc104e'></input><span>Frequentist: probability is the long-run relative frequency of outcomes in repeated trials</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='9d7618e256099eb232b4f8515cdc104e'></input><span>Frequentist: probability must be 0 or 1 before data are collected</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='9d7618e256099eb232b4f8515cdc104e'></input><span>Bayesian: probability represents a degree of belief given current information</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The statement is explicitly about assigning probability **before** collecting new data using existing information and expert knowledge. That is the Bayesian interpretation: probability is a **degree of belief** conditional on what you currently know.  

A frequentist interpretation typically treats probability as a long‑run frequency under repeated identical trials. It does not assign probabilities to fixed but unknown hypotheses (like “this reach is occupied”) in the same way Bayesians do.

:::

