::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


If events A and B are mutually exclusive, which statement is true?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-dcd360cf3d8c63abe84a19e208c1928c' data-answer='P1NIAhoAT1Zu'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dcd360cf3d8c63abe84a19e208c1928c'></input><span>P(A | B) = P(A)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dcd360cf3d8c63abe84a19e208c1928c'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) = 0</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dcd360cf3d8c63abe84a19e208c1928c'></input><span>P(A) = P(B)</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='dcd360cf3d8c63abe84a19e208c1928c'></input><span>A and B must be independent</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Mutually exclusive means **cannot happen together**, so the overlap is zero: P(A ∩ B) = 0. They are **not independent** unless one event has probability 0.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a salmon smolt study, you estimate P(survive | low flow) = 0.30 and P(survive) = 0.45. Which conclusion is most appropriate?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-b06a6684c6159e8288be51606761fd17' data-answer='OQEaURoGFAQ+'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b06a6684c6159e8288be51606761fd17'></input><span>Survival is lower under low flow than overall</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b06a6684c6159e8288be51606761fd17'></input><span>Low flow increases survival</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b06a6684c6159e8288be51606761fd17'></input><span>This proves low flow causes mortality</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='b06a6684c6159e8288be51606761fd17'></input><span>Survival and flow are independent</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Compare conditional to marginal probability: 0.30 < 0.45, so survival appears less likely under low flow than overall. That implies association (dependence).  However, it does not prove causation, as high flow could be correlated with other factors (timing, predators, turbidity). Probability comparisons identify patterns, whereas causal claims require mechanistic understanding and stronger design/analysis.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


A researcher studying amphibian occurrence samples a wetland in two consecutive days. The probability that amphibians are detected on a daily sample depends on the weather. Which statements could be true? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-01a874ff2f0f4d4b52500d6578de4b00' data-answer='awBNCBsESldv'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='01a874ff2f0f4d4b52500d6578de4b00'></input><span>If weather conditions persist, P(detect sample 2 | detect sample 1 ) could be higher than P(detect sample 2)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='01a874ff2f0f4d4b52500d6578de4b00'></input><span>Sampling in different days guarantees independence</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='01a874ff2f0f4d4b52500d6578de4b00'></input><span>Mutual exclusivity implies you cannot detect amphibians on both sampling days</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='01a874ff2f0f4d4b52500d6578de4b00'></input><span>Detecting amphibians in the two sampling days may be dependent because of weather effects</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Shared drivers (i.e., weather in this case) can create dependence across sampling days. Detecting amphibians on the first sampling day due good weather can indicate a high probability of detection on the second sampling day if weather conditions persist. Mutual exclusivity is not appropriate here because detecting in two consecutive days is possible.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statements correctly describe complements? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-f58045fe1f50aadb215f5316e56e6d24' data-answer='PQQUABgESlRs'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='f58045fe1f50aadb215f5316e56e6d24'></input><span>A ∪ Aᶜ equals the sample space</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='f58045fe1f50aadb215f5316e56e6d24'></input><span>A and Aᶜ are independent</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='f58045fe1f50aadb215f5316e56e6d24'></input><span>A and Aᶜ cannot occur together</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='f58045fe1f50aadb215f5316e56e6d24'></input><span>P(Aᶜ) = 1 − P(A)</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Complements are mutually exclusive (can't happen together) and exhaustive (one must happen), so their probabilities sum to 1. They are not independent unless P(A) = 0 or P(A) = 1, because knowing A occurred tells you Aᶜ did not occur.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statements are consistent with probability axioms (foundational statements) and rules (derivations fom axioms)? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-5b4c8cf6ec95f028fc67ec1908614eae' data-answer='blIYUhRSSgc4'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5b4c8cf6ec95f028fc67ec1908614eae'></input><span>P(A) can exceed 1 if A is common</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5b4c8cf6ec95f028fc67ec1908614eae'></input><span>Probabilities are non-negative</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5b4c8cf6ec95f028fc67ec1908614eae'></input><span>P(S) = 1 for sample space S (i.e., normalization)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5b4c8cf6ec95f028fc67ec1908614eae'></input><span>P(A) + P(Aᶜ) = 1</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Non‑negativity and normalization are axioms. The complement rule gives P(A) + P(Aᶜ) = 1. Probabilities never exceed 1.

:::

