:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Suppose P(A) = 0.6, P(B) = 0.5, P(A ∩ B) = 0.4. Which statements are true? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-5e1e37117f4c5f370652808c7af295ec' data-answer='blQdVB8GHQFq'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5e1e37117f4c5f370652808c7af295ec'></input><span>P(A | B) = 0.8</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5e1e37117f4c5f370652808c7af295ec'></input><span>A and B are not mutually exclusive</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5e1e37117f4c5f370652808c7af295ec'></input><span>P(A ∪ B) = 0.7</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='5e1e37117f4c5f370652808c7af295ec'></input><span>A and B are independent</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Compute union: 0.6 + 0.5 − 0.4 = 0.7. Independence would require 0.6 × 0.5 = 0.3, not 0.4. Intersection is not 0, so not mutually exclusive. Conditional: P(A | B) = 0.4 / 0.5 = 0.8.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


You survey a wetland and estimate that the probability a randomly chosen quadrat contains cattails is 0.65. Which interpretation is most appropriate under the frequentist definition of probability?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-2fc2ae2d8a792b9f888c174a3e636284' data-answer='aVZPA01VHlRl'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2fc2ae2d8a792b9f888c174a3e636284'></input><span>Cattails are guaranteed to be present in every wetland</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2fc2ae2d8a792b9f888c174a3e636284'></input><span>In the long run, about 65% of randomly sampled quadrats would contain cattails</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2fc2ae2d8a792b9f888c174a3e636284'></input><span>Exactly 65% of all quadrats always contain cattails</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='2fc2ae2d8a792b9f888c174a3e636284'></input><span>There are exactly 65 cattails per quadrat</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

A probability like 0.65 describes **uncertainty** and is often interpreted as a long‑run frequency by frequentists. That is, if you repeatedly sample many quadrats under similar conditions, you would expect cattails in about 65% of them **on average**. It does **not** mean you will get exactly 65% in every small sample, it does not describe abundance (how many cattails), and it does not guarantee they will be present in every wetland.

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which statements about conditional probability are correct? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-39f21af8a64a69ed9929ad957234dfe1' data-answer='aAhKAx1QSgg8'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='39f21af8a64a69ed9929ad957234dfe1'></input><span>If independent, P(A | B) = P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='39f21af8a64a69ed9929ad957234dfe1'></input><span>It can be larger or smaller than the marginal probability</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='39f21af8a64a69ed9929ad957234dfe1'></input><span>It uses information after the word 'given'</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='39f21af8a64a69ed9929ad957234dfe1'></input><span>It always increases probability</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Conditioning can increase or decrease probability depending on association. Independence means that conditioning does not change probabilities.

:::

