:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a habitat survey, A = “site is in forest”, B = “site has moss present”. Which statements are plausible? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-c854623216e36796036f46d75db162c0' data-answer='OAkZBBoDHwJs'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c854623216e36796036f46d75db162c0'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) ≤ P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c854623216e36796036f46d75db162c0'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) can be greater than P(A)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c854623216e36796036f46d75db162c0'></input><span>A and B could be dependent because forest microclimate supports moss</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='c854623216e36796036f46d75db162c0'></input><span>A and B must be independent because they are different attributes</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Dependence is plausible via dependence of moss on cool and humid microclimates, which can be provided by forests. The intersection cannot exceed either event, so P(A ∩ B) ≤ P(A).

:::

:::
::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Which conditions imply independence? Select all that apply.


<div class='webex-checkboxgroup' id='webex-4bc777a869dcdb572b715a862e991f51' data-answer='b1JPBhsGTQlr'><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4bc777a869dcdb572b715a862e991f51'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) = 0</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4bc777a869dcdb572b715a862e991f51'></input><span>P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4bc777a869dcdb572b715a862e991f51'></input><span>P(B | A) = P(B)</span></label><label><input type='checkbox' autocomplete='off' name='4bc777a869dcdb572b715a862e991f51'></input><span>P(A | B) = P(A)</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

The first three are equivalent characterizations of independence (when defined).
P(A ∩ B) = 0 is mutual exclusivity, not independence unless one event has probability 0.

:::

