::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


In a set of lakes, 40% have high nutrient levels (event N), so P(N) = 0.4. Historically, algal blooms (event B) have occurred in 35% of the lakes, so P(B) = 0.35.

Among lakes with high nutrient levels, 70% have algal blooms, so P(B | N) = 0.7.

What is the probability that a lake has high nutrient levels given that it exhibits an algal bloom?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-21956124b62412f6554bf758b6d3ee01' data-answer='aQEVBBoBHgQ/'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21956124b62412f6554bf758b6d3ee01'></input><span>0.2</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21956124b62412f6554bf758b6d3ee01'></input><span>0.8</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21956124b62412f6554bf758b6d3ee01'></input><span>0.4</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='21956124b62412f6554bf758b6d3ee01'></input><span>0.6</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

You are asked to find P(N | B). So, applying Bayes’ rule:

P(N | B) = [P(B | N) × P(N)] / P(B)
          = (0.7 × 0.4) / 0.35
          = 0.8

:::

