::: {.webex-question }
::: {.webex-check .webex-box}


Why is assuming independence often risky in ecology?


<div class='webex-radiogroup' id='webex-20e480dd35351501d4635d81892a9ba7' data-answer='aQBJBRQASFRu'><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='20e480dd35351501d4635d81892a9ba7'></input><span>Because probabilities cannot be estimated in ecology</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='20e480dd35351501d4635d81892a9ba7'></input><span>Because ecological processes are often linked by mechanisms</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='20e480dd35351501d4635d81892a9ba7'></input><span>Because independence violates axioms</span></label><label><input type='radio' autocomplete='off' name='20e480dd35351501d4635d81892a9ba7'></input><span>Because independence always reduces probabilities</span></label></div>


:::
::: {.webex-solution}

Ecological variables are frequently connected by causal pathways (temperature ↔ DO, habitat ↔ survival, predators ↔ prey). Independence is a strong simplifying assumption. When it fails, calculations like P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B) can be seriously misleading.

:::

